  "texts": [
    "The SHAP (Lundberg and Lee 2017) is a method inspired in game-theory that aims to enhance interpretability through the computation of the importance values for each features for individual predictions.",
    "There are several methods for computing the shapley values.",
    "It has three desirable properties: local accuracy, missingness (missing features get a value of 0), consistency (if the relative importance of a feature changes because of a model change, that is reflected on the SHAP values).",
    "Examples of SHAP applications are: Mosca et al. (2022), which uses the sentence structure to enhance interpretability; Le et al. (2022b), which combines BERT and SHAP to improve DNA analysis; Rizinski et al. (2022), which uses SHAP to promote ethically responsible ML in Fintech.",
    "SHAP's advantages are (Molnar 2022): solid theoretical foundation; has a fast implementation with tree-based models; it is possible to get a global interpretation of the model by computing several SHAP values."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "The SHAP (Lundberg and Lee 2017) is a method inspired in game-theory that aims to enhance interpretability through the computation of the importance values for each features for individual predictions.",
    "Examples of SHAP applications are: Mosca et al. (2022), which uses the sentence structure to enhance interpretability; Le et al. (2022b), which combines BERT and SHAP to improve DNA analysis; Rizinski et al. (2022), which uses SHAP to promote ethically responsible ML in Fintech.",
    "SHAP's advantages are (Molnar 2022): solid theoretical foundation; has a fast implementation with tree-based models; it is possible to get a global interpretation of the model by computing several SHAP values."
